{"type":"user","message":{"role":"user","content":[{"tool_use_id":"toolu_01Dz56jfyALtNuCWBW72dTZW","type":"tool_result","content":"     1→# Iteration 29 → 30 Improvement Plan\n     2→\n     3→**Status:** Draft\n     4→**Date:** 2026-03-17\n     5→**Baseline:** 91.9% combined accuracy (9 failures, all generated; 0 real failures)\n     6→\n     7→---\n     8→\n     9→## Overview\n    10→\n    11→Nine generated-file failures remain, clustered into three root causes:\n    12→\n    13→1. **Incomplete mixed-case OCR repair** — the blind repair path (`applyBlindOcrRepairToken`) only substitutes `1→i/l`, `¡→i`, `€→e` in mixed-case context. It misses `0→o`, `4→a`, `5→s`, which the ALL_CAPS branch handles. This causes Pattern 7 (partial repair) and contributes to Patterns 1–4 where partially-repaired titles fail hard filters or score poorly.\n    14→\n    15→2. **Missing Polish cooking verb prefixes** — `looksLikeCookingInstruction` and `POLISH_COOKING_INSTRUCTION_STARTS` don't cover perfective forms like `ugotuj` (u+gotuj), `upiecz` (u+piecz), `podawać/podaw4ć` (serve). Body lines starting with these verbs pass hard filters and can outscore the actual title.\n    16→\n    17→3. **Garbled tokens evade multi-word detection** — `isLikelyGarbled` catches single-word `[a-z][A-Z]` transitions (line 302) but not multi-word candidates containing such tokens. `XxYyZz salt and pepper` passes because the garbled check only fires for `words.length === 1`.\n    18→\n    19→Pattern 6 (Mushroom Risotto — title absent from document) is a structural/scan problem where the actual recipe title doesn't appear in the text. The extractor correctly identifies the best title-like line; it's just the wrong recipe. This is **not fixable** without external context and is excluded from this plan.\n    20→\n    21→---\n    22→\n    23→## Goals\n    24→\n    25→- Fix Patterns 1, 2, 3, 4, 5, 7 (8 of 9 failures)\n    26→- Maintain 100% accuracy on real files\n    27→- No regressions on currently-passing generated files\n    28→- Keep total extraction time under 10 seconds on device\n    29→\n    30→## Non-Goals\n    31→\n    32→- Fix Pattern 6 (title absent from document) — requires page-level context\n    33→- Change the embedding model or similarity strategy — MiniLM works well for the 102+ passing cases\n    34→- Restructure the candidate generation pipeline — it's architecturally sound\n    35→\n    36→---\n    37→\n    38→## Detailed Changes\n    39→\n    40→### Change A: Complete mixed-case blind OCR repair\n    41→\n    42→**File:** `lib/text-classifier/title-extractor.ts`, function `applyBlindOcrRepairToken` (lines 845–857)\n    43→\n    44→**Problem:** The mixed-case branch only handles three substitutions:\n    45→```typescript\n    46→// Current mixed-case path (lines 852-856):\n    47→.replace(/(?<=[a-zà-ż])1/g, oneLetter)\n    48→.replace(/1(?=[a-zà-ż])/g, oneLetter)\n    49→.replace(/¡/g, \"i\")\n    50→.replace(/€/g, \"e\")\n    51→```\n    52→\n    53→Missing: `0→o`, `4→a`, `5→s` — all present in the ALL_CAPS branch (lines 879–884) but absent from mixed-case. This directly causes Pattern 7 (`S01e` → `S0ie` instead of `Sole`) and weakens repair of Patterns 1–4.\n    54→\n    55→**Fix:** Add the missing substitutions with lowercase-adjacent context guards:\n    56→```typescript\n    57→// After the existing 1→oneLetter and ¡→i replacements, add:\n    58→.replace(/(?<=[a-zà-ż])0/g, \"o\")\n    59→.replace(/0(?=[a-zà-ż])/g, \"o\")\n    60→.replace(/(?<=[a-zà-ż])4/g, \"a\")\n    61→.replace(/4(?=[a-zà-ż])/g, \"a\")\n    62→.replace(/(?<=[a-zà-ż])5/g, \"s\")\n    63→.replace(/5(?=[a-zà-ż])/g, \"s\")\n    64→```\n    65→\n    66→The lookaround guards (requiring adjacent lowercase letters) prevent false positives on legitimate digits in titles like \"Variation 4\" or \"Page 50\".\n    67→\n    68→**Also update `generateBlindOcrVariants`** (lines 920–938): the dual-variant logic currently only varies `1→i` vs `1→l`. With `0→o` added, `S01e` will now produce `Sole` in a single pass (both `0→o` and `1→i` fire). No dual-variant needed for `0`.\n    69→\n    70→**Impact:** Fixes Pattern 7 directly. Strengthens repair for Patterns 1–4 by ensuring the blind repair path produces cleaner candidates that score better in embeddings.\n    71→\n    72→**Risk:** Low. The lookaround guards prevent over-application. The ALL_CAPS branch already applies these substitutions unconditionally.\n    73→\n    74→---\n    75→\n    76→### Change B: Expand garbled token detection to multi-word candidates\n    77→\n    78→**File:** `lib/text-classifier/title-extractor.ts`, function `isLikelyGarbled` (lines 271–337)\n    79→\n    80→**Problem:** The `[a-z][A-Z]` internal transition check (line 302) only fires for single-word candidates (`words.length === 1`). Multi-word candidates like `XxYyZz salt and pepper` pass because `XxYyZz` is never checked individually for the transition pattern.\n    81→\n    82→**Fix:** Add a multi-word garbled token check alongside the existing short-word check (lines 318–333):\n    83→\n    84→```typescript\n    85→// After the existing short-word check (line 331-333), add:\n    86→// Multi-word candidate with a garbled token: a word with internal\n    87→// lowercase→uppercase transition that isn't a known camelCase pattern\n    88→// (e.g., \"McDonald\", \"McCormick\"). Catches \"XxYyZz\", \"UuIw\" etc.\n    89→const hasGarbledCamelCase = words.some(\n    90→  (w) =>\n    91→    w.length >= 3 &&\n    92→    /[a-z][A-Z]/.test(w) &&\n    93→    !/^(Mc|Mac)[A-Z]/.test(w)  // Exempt Scottish/Irish names\n    94→);\n    95→if (hasGarbledCamelCase) {\n    96→  return true;\n    97→}\n    98→```\n    99→\n   100→**Impact:** Fixes Pattern 3 (Żurek Krakowski → `XxYyZz salt and pepper`). The garbage token `XxYyZz` triggers the `[a-z][A-Z]` check, causing the entire candidate to be rejected by hard filters. The clean title `Żurek Krakowski` at position 0 then wins.\n   101→\n   102→**Risk:** Low. Legitimate recipe titles never contain camelCase words. The `Mc`/`Mac` exemption handles the only realistic edge case (e.g., \"McCormick Spice Blend\"), though this pattern is unlikely in recipe OCR.\n   103→\n   104→---\n   105→\n   106→### Change C: Expand Polish cooking verb filter\n   107→\n   108→**File:** `lib/text-classifier/title-extractor.ts`, `POLISH_COOKING_INSTRUCTION_STARTS` (line 346)\n   109→\n   110→**Problem:** The regex misses common perfective-prefix verbs:\n   111→- `ugotuj` (u+gotuj = \"cook [to completion]\") — causes Pattern 4 (`Ugotuj ziemniaky. (38)` wins)\n   112→- `upiecz` (u+piecz = \"bake [to completion]\")\n   113→- `usmaż` is already covered, but `upiecz` and `ugotuj` are not\n   114→- `podawaj` is covered, but `podaw` without the full suffix isn't (OCR-corrupted `Podaw4ć` → after repair → `Podawać`)\n   115→\n   116→**Fix:** Add missing verb forms to `POLISH_COOKING_INSTRUCTION_STARTS`:\n   117→\n   118→```typescript\n   119→// Add to the alternation group:\n   120→ugotuj|ugotowac|upiecz|usmaz    // perfective u- prefix forms\n   121→|podawa[cć]                      // infinitive form of \"serve\"\n   122→|zapiekaj                        // \"bake in oven\"\n   123→|obtocz|obtoczyc                 // \"coat/roll in\"\n   124→|podgrzej|podgrzewaj             // \"reheat/warm up\"\n   125→```\n   126→\n   127→Also add a catch-all for OCR-corrupted Polish verbs: lines ending with `4ć` (OCR for `ać`) that start with a known cooking-verb stem should be treated as cooking instructions. This can be done by adding an OCR-aware variant to the regex or by normalizing `4→a` before the instruction check.\n   128→\n   129→**Impact:** Fixes Patterns 2 and 4 where `Podaw4ć ...` or `Ugotuj ...` body lines outscore the title. Once these lines are filtered as cooking instructions, they never enter the candidate pool.\n   130→\n   131→**Risk:** Low. These are unambiguous cooking verbs that never start recipe titles. `Ugotuj` is always imperative (≠ title). `Podawać` is always an instruction (≠ title).\n   132→\n   133→---\n   134→\n   135→### Change D: Pre-filter OCR normalization for cooking instruction detection\n   136→\n   137→**File:** `lib/text-classifier/title-extractor.ts`, function `looksLikeCookingInstruction` (line 348) and function `passesHardFilters` (line 385)\n   138→\n   139→**Problem:** `Podaw4ć letni lub chłodny.` fails the cooking instruction check because `Podaw4ć` doesn't match any verb pattern (the `4` breaks the regex). The line passes hard filters and becomes a candidate. After OCR repair it might become `Podawać letni lub chłodny.` but by then it's already in the pool.\n   140→\n   141→**Fix:** In `passesHardFilters`, apply lightweight OCR normalization (`4→a`, `1→i`, `0→o`, `5→s`) to the text **before** checking `looksLikeCookingInstruction`:\n   142→\n   143→```typescript\n   144→function passesHardFilters(text: string): boolean {\n   145→  if (text.length < 3 || text.length > 80) return false;\n   146→  if (looksLikeIngredient(text)) return false;\n   147→  if (startsWithNumber(text)) return false;\n   148→  if (looksLikeMetadata(text)) return false;\n   149→  if (isLikelyGarbled(text)) return false;\n   150→  // Apply lightweight OCR normalization before instruction check\n   151→  // so that \"Podaw4ć\" is recognized as \"Podawać\" (cooking instruction)\n   152→  const ocrNormalized = text\n   153→    .replace(/4(?=[a-zà-żA-ZÀ-Ż])/g, (_, offset) =>\n   154→      /[A-ZÀ-Ż]/.test(text[offset]) ? \"A\" : \"a\")\n   155→    .replace(/(?<=[a-zà-żA-ZÀ-Ż])4/g, (_, offset) =>\n   156→      /[A-ZÀ-Ż]/.test(text[offset - 1]) ? \"A\" : \"a\");\n   157→  if (looksLikeCookingInstruction(ocrNormalized)) return false;\n   158→  // ... rest of existing checks\n   159→```\n   160→\n   161→This is a targeted normalization (only `4→a` for now, since that's the specific failure), not the full blind repair. It runs before the instruction check so corrupted Polish verbs are correctly identified.\n   162→\n   163→**Impact:** Directly fixes Patterns 2 cases (`Podaw4ć letni lub chłodny.` and `Podaw4ć ciepło ze śmietaną lub lodami.`) by preventing them from entering the candidate pool.\n   164→\n   165→**Risk:** Low. `4` adjacent to letters is almost always an OCR artifact, not a legitimate digit. Recipe titles don't contain `4` adjacent to letters.\n   166→\n   167→---\n   168→\n   169→### Change E: Strengthen first-after-metadata positional bonus\n   170→\n   171→**File:** `lib/text-classifier/title-extractor.ts`, first-after-preamble bonus (lines 1121–1149)\n   172→\n   173→**Problem:** Pattern 5 (Ogórkowa Zupa) — the document starts with pipe-separated metadata, then a blank line, then the ALL_CAPS title. The first-after-preamble bonus fires (all preceding lines are filtered), but the bonus may not be enough to overcome a weak embedding score for Polish ALL_CAPS text in the MiniLM model.\n   174→\n   175→**Investigation needed:** Confirm whether `OGÓRKOWA ZUPA` is actually entering the candidate pool and what its raw embedding score is. The MiniLM model is English-centric and may score Polish ALL_CAPS titles very poorly (negative rawScore), causing them to fall below even the relaxed fallback threshold.\n   176→\n   177→**Fix (two-part):**\n   178→\n   179→**Part 1:** In the empty-pool fallback (lines 1371–1381), relax the rawScore threshold for position-0 candidates that have structural evidence (first-after-preamble or direct-successor). Currently the threshold is `-0.05` for position ≤ 2. For candidates with confirmed structural preamble (section label or metadata on the preceding line), lower it to `-0.10`:\n   180→\n   181→```typescript\n   182→if (selected.length === 0 && scored.length > 0) {\n   183→  const fallback = scored\n   184→    .slice()\n   185→    .sort((a, b) => a.position - b.position || b.score - a.score);\n   186→  // Stronger relaxation for candidates with structural evidence\n   187→  const hasStructuralEvidence = /* check first-after-preamble or direct-successor fired */;\n   188→  const rawScoreThreshold = hasStructuralEvidence ? -0.10\n   189→    : fallback[0].position <= 2 ? -0.05\n   190→    : 0.02;\n   191→  if (fallback[0].rawScore > rawScoreThreshold) {\n   192→    selected = [fallback[0]];\n   193→  }\n   194→}\n   195→```\n   196→\n   197→**Part 2:** If the above doesn't fix it (because the candidate doesn't reach the fallback), increase the preamble bonus from `0.12` to `0.15` when the preamble contains pipe-separated metadata AND the candidate is ALL_CAPS. This is strong structural evidence — pipe-separated metadata followed by ALL_CAPS text is a near-certain title pattern in Polish cookbooks.\n   198→\n   199→**Impact:** Fixes Pattern 5. The pipe-separated metadata line is correctly filtered, and the ALL_CAPS title immediately after gets sufficient positional boost to overcome weak Polish embedding signal.\n   200→\n   201→**Risk:** Medium-low. The stronger fallback threshold only applies when structural evidence is present (metadata/section label before the candidate), which is a reliable signal. The cap at +0.15 (line 1182) prevents over-boosting.\n   202→\n   203→---\n   204→\n   205→### Change F: Add `(N)` trailing page/step number stripping\n   206→\n   207→**File:** `lib/text-classifier/title-extractor.ts`, function `passesHardFilters` (line 385) or `stripPageNumber` (line 521)\n   208→\n   209→**Problem:** `Ugotuj ziemniaky. (38)` — the `(38)` suffix is a page or step number that isn't caught by existing filters. This contributes to Pattern 4 where the instruction line passes filters and scores well.\n   210→\n   211→**Fix:** Add a stripping rule for trailing parenthesized numbers:\n   212→\n   213→```typescript\n   214→function stripTrailingPageRef(text: string): string {\n   215→  // \"Ugotuj ziemniaky. (38)\" → \"Ugotuj ziemniaky.\"\n   216→  // \"RECIPE NAME (p. 42)\" → \"RECIPE NAME\"\n   217→  return text.replace(/\\s*\\((?:p\\.?\\s*)?\\d{1,4}\\)\\s*$/, \"\").trim();\n   218→}\n   219→```\n   220→\n   221→Apply this in `buildCandidates` alongside `stripPageNumber` and `stripParentheticalGloss` (line 648). After stripping, the `isLikelyGarbled` mid-sentence-boundary check (`. ` followed by letter) won't be confused by the page ref.\n   222→\n   223→**Impact:** Minor supporting fix for Pattern 4. The main fix is Change C (cooking verb filter), but this strips noise that could affect scoring.\n   224→\n   225→**Risk:** Low. Trailing `(N)` where N is 1–4 digits is never part of a recipe title.\n   226→\n   227→---\n   228→\n   229→## Testing Strategy\n   230→\n   231→### Unit tests to add\n   232→\n   233→1. **Mixed-case OCR repair completeness:**\n   234→   - `applyBlindOcrRepairToken(\"S01e\", \"i\")` → `\"Sole\"` (0→o + 1→i)\n   235→   - `applyBlindOcrRepairToken(\"m4ki\", \"i\")` → `\"maki\"` (4→a)\n   236→   - `applyBlindOcrRepairToken(\"P5eudo\", \"i\")` → `\"Pseudo\"` (5→s)\n   237→   - `applyBlindOcrRepairToken(\"test5\", \"i\")` → `\"tests\"` (5→s at end)\n   238→\n   239→2. **Garbled multi-word detection:**\n   240→   - `isLikelyGarbled(\"XxYyZz salt and pepper\")` → `true`\n   241→   - `isLikelyGarbled(\"McDonald Spice Blend\")` → `false` (Mc exemption)\n   242→   - `isLikelyGarbled(\"Żurek Krakowski\")` → `false`\n   243→\n   244→3. **Polish cooking verb expansion:**\n   245→   - `looksLikeCookingInstruction(\"Ugotuj ziemniaki w osolonej wodzie.\")` → `true`\n   246→   - `looksLikeCookingInstruction(\"Podawać letni lub chłodny.\")` → `true`\n   247→   - `looksLikeCookingInstruction(\"Ugotuj\")` → `false` (< 4 words)\n   248→\n   249→4. **OCR-normalized instruction detection:**\n   250→   - `passesHardFilters(\"Podaw4ć letni lub chłodny.\")` → `false` (cooking instruction after OCR norm)\n   251→\n   252→### Integration tests (eval loop)\n   253→\n   254→Run the full evaluation suite against all 111 test files. Expected outcomes:\n   255→- 0 regressions on currently-passing files\n   256→- 8 newly-passing files (all except Mushroom Risotto)\n   257→- Target: ≥99% combined accuracy (≤2 failures)\n   258→\n   259→---\n   260→\n   261→## Performance Considerations\n   262→\n   263→All changes are O(1) per candidate (regex replacements, string checks). No additional embedding calls. No new async operations. Total impact on extraction time: negligible (< 1ms).\n   264→\n   265→---\n   266→\n   267→## Implementation Order\n   268→\n   269→Changes are independent and can be implemented in any order. However, the recommended order maximizes incremental testability:\n   270→\n   271→1. **Change B** (garbled multi-word) — simplest, one check addition, fixes Pattern 3\n   272→2. **Change C** (Polish verbs) — small regex expansion, fixes Pattern 2 partially\n   273→3. **Change D** (OCR-normalized instruction check) — completes Pattern 2 fix\n   274→4. **Change A** (mixed-case OCR repair) — addresses Patterns 1, 4, 7\n   275→5. **Change F** (trailing page ref) — minor cleanup\n   276→6. **Change E** (positional bonus) — Pattern 5, needs investigation if still needed after A–D\n   277→\n   278→---\n   279→\n   280→## Open Questions\n   281→\n   282→1. **Pattern 5 root cause:** Is `OGÓRKOWA ZUPA` actually entering the candidate pool? If the raw embedding score for Polish ALL_CAPS is very negative, Change E alone may not suffice. May need to log scoring details for this specific test case during implementation.\n   283→\n   284→2. **Dictionary coverage for `with/the/a`:** The food dictionary includes `\"with\"` (line 135), so `w1th` should be dictionary-repaired to `with`. If the dictionary-guided repair already fixes most artifacts for Patterns 1–2, the blind repair improvement (Change A) may be redundant for those cases. But it's still needed for Pattern 7 and words not in the dictionary.\n   285→\n   286→3. **`4→a` lookaround precision:** The current `0→O` substitution in the ALL_CAPS branch uses `(?<=[A-ZÀ-Ż])0` — requiring adjacent uppercase. For mixed-case, should we require BOTH adjacent characters to be letters, or just one? Single-sided lookaround matches more cases but has a slightly higher false-positive risk (e.g., `m4` in an ingredient line like `300g m4ki pszenne`). However, ingredient lines are already filtered by `looksLikeIngredient`, so the risk is minimal.\n   287→\n   288→---\n   289→\n   290→## Failure → Fix Mapping\n   291→\n   292→| Pattern | Failures | Root cause | Primary fix | Secondary fix |\n   293→|---------|----------|-----------|-------------|---------------|\n   294→| 1: OCR → empty | 2 | Corrupted title rejected, no fallback | A (complete OCR repair) | E (relaxed fallback) |\n   295→| 2: OCR → wrong body | 2 | Body line (`Podaw4ć...`) outscores title | C (Polish verbs) + D (OCR-norm filter) | A (better repair) |\n   296→| 3: Garbage → wrong body | 1 | `XxYyZz` evades garbled check | B (multi-word garbled) | — |\n   297→| 4: Erratic case → wrong body | 1 | `Ugotuj ziemniaky. (38)` wins | C (Polish verbs) + A (OCR repair) | F (page ref strip) |\n   298→| 5: Metadata → empty | 1 | Polish ALL_CAPS weak embedding | E (positional bonus) | A (may help indirectly) |\n   299→| 6: Title absent | 1 | Structural problem | **Not fixable** | — |\n   300→| 7: Partial OCR | 1 | `0→o` missing in mixed-case | A (complete OCR repair) | — |\n   301→"}]},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"a92866c1-134f-4711-bade-a1c8bcc36679","uuid":"7e9fdf50-4c48-4b76-89a5-a014c4978678","tool_use_result":{"type":"text","file":{"filePath":"/Users/eryk.napierala/Projects/fasola/tools/title-loop/docs/29-e7e3098/improvement-plan.md","content":"# Iteration 29 → 30 Improvement Plan\n\n**Status:** Draft\n**Date:** 2026-03-17\n**Baseline:** 91.9% combined accuracy (9 failures, all generated; 0 real failures)\n\n---\n\n## Overview\n\nNine generated-file failures remain, clustered into three root causes:\n\n1. **Incomplete mixed-case OCR repair** — the blind repair path (`applyBlindOcrRepairToken`) only substitutes `1→i/l`, `¡→i`, `€→e` in mixed-case context. It misses `0→o`, `4→a`, `5→s`, which the ALL_CAPS branch handles. This causes Pattern 7 (partial repair) and contributes to Patterns 1–4 where partially-repaired titles fail hard filters or score poorly.\n\n2. **Missing Polish cooking verb prefixes** — `looksLikeCookingInstruction` and `POLISH_COOKING_INSTRUCTION_STARTS` don't cover perfective forms like `ugotuj` (u+gotuj), `upiecz` (u+piecz), `podawać/podaw4ć` (serve). Body lines starting with these verbs pass hard filters and can outscore the actual title.\n\n3. **Garbled tokens evade multi-word detection** — `isLikelyGarbled` catches single-word `[a-z][A-Z]` transitions (line 302) but not multi-word candidates containing such tokens. `XxYyZz salt and pepper` passes because the garbled check only fires for `words.length === 1`.\n\nPattern 6 (Mushroom Risotto — title absent from document) is a structural/scan problem where the actual recipe title doesn't appear in the text. The extractor correctly identifies the best title-like line; it's just the wrong recipe. This is **not fixable** without external context and is excluded from this plan.\n\n---\n\n## Goals\n\n- Fix Patterns 1, 2, 3, 4, 5, 7 (8 of 9 failures)\n- Maintain 100% accuracy on real files\n- No regressions on currently-passing generated files\n- Keep total extraction time under 10 seconds on device\n\n## Non-Goals\n\n- Fix Pattern 6 (title absent from document) — requires page-level context\n- Change the embedding model or similarity strategy — MiniLM works well for the 102+ passing cases\n- Restructure the candidate generation pipeline — it's architecturally sound\n\n---\n\n## Detailed Changes\n\n### Change A: Complete mixed-case blind OCR repair\n\n**File:** `lib/text-classifier/title-extractor.ts`, function `applyBlindOcrRepairToken` (lines 845–857)\n\n**Problem:** The mixed-case branch only handles three substitutions:\n```typescript\n// Current mixed-case path (lines 852-856):\n.replace(/(?<=[a-zà-ż])1/g, oneLetter)\n.replace(/1(?=[a-zà-ż])/g, oneLetter)\n.replace(/¡/g, \"i\")\n.replace(/€/g, \"e\")\n```\n\nMissing: `0→o`, `4→a`, `5→s` — all present in the ALL_CAPS branch (lines 879–884) but absent from mixed-case. This directly causes Pattern 7 (`S01e` → `S0ie` instead of `Sole`) and weakens repair of Patterns 1–4.\n\n**Fix:** Add the missing substitutions with lowercase-adjacent context guards:\n```typescript\n// After the existing 1→oneLetter and ¡→i replacements, add:\n.replace(/(?<=[a-zà-ż])0/g, \"o\")\n.replace(/0(?=[a-zà-ż])/g, \"o\")\n.replace(/(?<=[a-zà-ż])4/g, \"a\")\n.replace(/4(?=[a-zà-ż])/g, \"a\")\n.replace(/(?<=[a-zà-ż])5/g, \"s\")\n.replace(/5(?=[a-zà-ż])/g, \"s\")\n```\n\nThe lookaround guards (requiring adjacent lowercase letters) prevent false positives on legitimate digits in titles like \"Variation 4\" or \"Page 50\".\n\n**Also update `generateBlindOcrVariants`** (lines 920–938): the dual-variant logic currently only varies `1→i` vs `1→l`. With `0→o` added, `S01e` will now produce `Sole` in a single pass (both `0→o` and `1→i` fire). No dual-variant needed for `0`.\n\n**Impact:** Fixes Pattern 7 directly. Strengthens repair for Patterns 1–4 by ensuring the blind repair path produces cleaner candidates that score better in embeddings.\n\n**Risk:** Low. The lookaround guards prevent over-application. The ALL_CAPS branch already applies these substitutions unconditionally.\n\n---\n\n### Change B: Expand garbled token detection to multi-word candidates\n\n**File:** `lib/text-classifier/title-extractor.ts`, function `isLikelyGarbled` (lines 271–337)\n\n**Problem:** The `[a-z][A-Z]` internal transition check (line 302) only fires for single-word candidates (`words.length === 1`). Multi-word candidates like `XxYyZz salt and pepper` pass because `XxYyZz` is never checked individually for the transition pattern.\n\n**Fix:** Add a multi-word garbled token check alongside the existing short-word check (lines 318–333):\n\n```typescript\n// After the existing short-word check (line 331-333), add:\n// Multi-word candidate with a garbled token: a word with internal\n// lowercase→uppercase transition that isn't a known camelCase pattern\n// (e.g., \"McDonald\", \"McCormick\"). Catches \"XxYyZz\", \"UuIw\" etc.\nconst hasGarbledCamelCase = words.some(\n  (w) =>\n    w.length >= 3 &&\n    /[a-z][A-Z]/.test(w) &&\n    !/^(Mc|Mac)[A-Z]/.test(w)  // Exempt Scottish/Irish names\n);\nif (hasGarbledCamelCase) {\n  return true;\n}\n```\n\n**Impact:** Fixes Pattern 3 (Żurek Krakowski → `XxYyZz salt and pepper`). The garbage token `XxYyZz` triggers the `[a-z][A-Z]` check, causing the entire candidate to be rejected by hard filters. The clean title `Żurek Krakowski` at position 0 then wins.\n\n**Risk:** Low. Legitimate recipe titles never contain camelCase words. The `Mc`/`Mac` exemption handles the only realistic edge case (e.g., \"McCormick Spice Blend\"), though this pattern is unlikely in recipe OCR.\n\n---\n\n### Change C: Expand Polish cooking verb filter\n\n**File:** `lib/text-classifier/title-extractor.ts`, `POLISH_COOKING_INSTRUCTION_STARTS` (line 346)\n\n**Problem:** The regex misses common perfective-prefix verbs:\n- `ugotuj` (u+gotuj = \"cook [to completion]\") — causes Pattern 4 (`Ugotuj ziemniaky. (38)` wins)\n- `upiecz` (u+piecz = \"bake [to completion]\")\n- `usmaż` is already covered, but `upiecz` and `ugotuj` are not\n- `podawaj` is covered, but `podaw` without the full suffix isn't (OCR-corrupted `Podaw4ć` → after repair → `Podawać`)\n\n**Fix:** Add missing verb forms to `POLISH_COOKING_INSTRUCTION_STARTS`:\n\n```typescript\n// Add to the alternation group:\nugotuj|ugotowac|upiecz|usmaz    // perfective u- prefix forms\n|podawa[cć]                      // infinitive form of \"serve\"\n|zapiekaj                        // \"bake in oven\"\n|obtocz|obtoczyc                 // \"coat/roll in\"\n|podgrzej|podgrzewaj             // \"reheat/warm up\"\n```\n\nAlso add a catch-all for OCR-corrupted Polish verbs: lines ending with `4ć` (OCR for `ać`) that start with a known cooking-verb stem should be treated as cooking instructions. This can be done by adding an OCR-aware variant to the regex or by normalizing `4→a` before the instruction check.\n\n**Impact:** Fixes Patterns 2 and 4 where `Podaw4ć ...` or `Ugotuj ...` body lines outscore the title. Once these lines are filtered as cooking instructions, they never enter the candidate pool.\n\n**Risk:** Low. These are unambiguous cooking verbs that never start recipe titles. `Ugotuj` is always imperative (≠ title). `Podawać` is always an instruction (≠ title).\n\n---\n\n### Change D: Pre-filter OCR normalization for cooking instruction detection\n\n**File:** `lib/text-classifier/title-extractor.ts`, function `looksLikeCookingInstruction` (line 348) and function `passesHardFilters` (line 385)\n\n**Problem:** `Podaw4ć letni lub chłodny.` fails the cooking instruction check because `Podaw4ć` doesn't match any verb pattern (the `4` breaks the regex). The line passes hard filters and becomes a candidate. After OCR repair it might become `Podawać letni lub chłodny.` but by then it's already in the pool.\n\n**Fix:** In `passesHardFilters`, apply lightweight OCR normalization (`4→a`, `1→i`, `0→o`, `5→s`) to the text **before** checking `looksLikeCookingInstruction`:\n\n```typescript\nfunction passesHardFilters(text: string): boolean {\n  if (text.length < 3 || text.length > 80) return false;\n  if (looksLikeIngredient(text)) return false;\n  if (startsWithNumber(text)) return false;\n  if (looksLikeMetadata(text)) return false;\n  if (isLikelyGarbled(text)) return false;\n  // Apply lightweight OCR normalization before instruction check\n  // so that \"Podaw4ć\" is recognized as \"Podawać\" (cooking instruction)\n  const ocrNormalized = text\n    .replace(/4(?=[a-zà-żA-ZÀ-Ż])/g, (_, offset) =>\n      /[A-ZÀ-Ż]/.test(text[offset]) ? \"A\" : \"a\")\n    .replace(/(?<=[a-zà-żA-ZÀ-Ż])4/g, (_, offset) =>\n      /[A-ZÀ-Ż]/.test(text[offset - 1]) ? \"A\" : \"a\");\n  if (looksLikeCookingInstruction(ocrNormalized)) return false;\n  // ... rest of existing checks\n```\n\nThis is a targeted normalization (only `4→a` for now, since that's the specific failure), not the full blind repair. It runs before the instruction check so corrupted Polish verbs are correctly identified.\n\n**Impact:** Directly fixes Patterns 2 cases (`Podaw4ć letni lub chłodny.` and `Podaw4ć ciepło ze śmietaną lub lodami.`) by preventing them from entering the candidate pool.\n\n**Risk:** Low. `4` adjacent to letters is almost always an OCR artifact, not a legitimate digit. Recipe titles don't contain `4` adjacent to letters.\n\n---\n\n### Change E: Strengthen first-after-metadata positional bonus\n\n**File:** `lib/text-classifier/title-extractor.ts`, first-after-preamble bonus (lines 1121–1149)\n\n**Problem:** Pattern 5 (Ogórkowa Zupa) — the document starts with pipe-separated metadata, then a blank line, then the ALL_CAPS title. The first-after-preamble bonus fires (all preceding lines are filtered), but the bonus may not be enough to overcome a weak embedding score for Polish ALL_CAPS text in the MiniLM model.\n\n**Investigation needed:** Confirm whether `OGÓRKOWA ZUPA` is actually entering the candidate pool and what its raw embedding score is. The MiniLM model is English-centric and may score Polish ALL_CAPS titles very poorly (negative rawScore), causing them to fall below even the relaxed fallback threshold.\n\n**Fix (two-part):**\n\n**Part 1:** In the empty-pool fallback (lines 1371–1381), relax the rawScore threshold for position-0 candidates that have structural evidence (first-after-preamble or direct-successor). Currently the threshold is `-0.05` for position ≤ 2. For candidates with confirmed structural preamble (section label or metadata on the preceding line), lower it to `-0.10`:\n\n```typescript\nif (selected.length === 0 && scored.length > 0) {\n  const fallback = scored\n    .slice()\n    .sort((a, b) => a.position - b.position || b.score - a.score);\n  // Stronger relaxation for candidates with structural evidence\n  const hasStructuralEvidence = /* check first-after-preamble or direct-successor fired */;\n  const rawScoreThreshold = hasStructuralEvidence ? -0.10\n    : fallback[0].position <= 2 ? -0.05\n    : 0.02;\n  if (fallback[0].rawScore > rawScoreThreshold) {\n    selected = [fallback[0]];\n  }\n}\n```\n\n**Part 2:** If the above doesn't fix it (because the candidate doesn't reach the fallback), increase the preamble bonus from `0.12` to `0.15` when the preamble contains pipe-separated metadata AND the candidate is ALL_CAPS. This is strong structural evidence — pipe-separated metadata followed by ALL_CAPS text is a near-certain title pattern in Polish cookbooks.\n\n**Impact:** Fixes Pattern 5. The pipe-separated metadata line is correctly filtered, and the ALL_CAPS title immediately after gets sufficient positional boost to overcome weak Polish embedding signal.\n\n**Risk:** Medium-low. The stronger fallback threshold only applies when structural evidence is present (metadata/section label before the candidate), which is a reliable signal. The cap at +0.15 (line 1182) prevents over-boosting.\n\n---\n\n### Change F: Add `(N)` trailing page/step number stripping\n\n**File:** `lib/text-classifier/title-extractor.ts`, function `passesHardFilters` (line 385) or `stripPageNumber` (line 521)\n\n**Problem:** `Ugotuj ziemniaky. (38)` — the `(38)` suffix is a page or step number that isn't caught by existing filters. This contributes to Pattern 4 where the instruction line passes filters and scores well.\n\n**Fix:** Add a stripping rule for trailing parenthesized numbers:\n\n```typescript\nfunction stripTrailingPageRef(text: string): string {\n  // \"Ugotuj ziemniaky. (38)\" → \"Ugotuj ziemniaky.\"\n  // \"RECIPE NAME (p. 42)\" → \"RECIPE NAME\"\n  return text.replace(/\\s*\\((?:p\\.?\\s*)?\\d{1,4}\\)\\s*$/, \"\").trim();\n}\n```\n\nApply this in `buildCandidates` alongside `stripPageNumber` and `stripParentheticalGloss` (line 648). After stripping, the `isLikelyGarbled` mid-sentence-boundary check (`. ` followed by letter) won't be confused by the page ref.\n\n**Impact:** Minor supporting fix for Pattern 4. The main fix is Change C (cooking verb filter), but this strips noise that could affect scoring.\n\n**Risk:** Low. Trailing `(N)` where N is 1–4 digits is never part of a recipe title.\n\n---\n\n## Testing Strategy\n\n### Unit tests to add\n\n1. **Mixed-case OCR repair completeness:**\n   - `applyBlindOcrRepairToken(\"S01e\", \"i\")` → `\"Sole\"` (0→o + 1→i)\n   - `applyBlindOcrRepairToken(\"m4ki\", \"i\")` → `\"maki\"` (4→a)\n   - `applyBlindOcrRepairToken(\"P5eudo\", \"i\")` → `\"Pseudo\"` (5→s)\n   - `applyBlindOcrRepairToken(\"test5\", \"i\")` → `\"tests\"` (5→s at end)\n\n2. **Garbled multi-word detection:**\n   - `isLikelyGarbled(\"XxYyZz salt and pepper\")` → `true`\n   - `isLikelyGarbled(\"McDonald Spice Blend\")` → `false` (Mc exemption)\n   - `isLikelyGarbled(\"Żurek Krakowski\")` → `false`\n\n3. **Polish cooking verb expansion:**\n   - `looksLikeCookingInstruction(\"Ugotuj ziemniaki w osolonej wodzie.\")` → `true`\n   - `looksLikeCookingInstruction(\"Podawać letni lub chłodny.\")` → `true`\n   - `looksLikeCookingInstruction(\"Ugotuj\")` → `false` (< 4 words)\n\n4. **OCR-normalized instruction detection:**\n   - `passesHardFilters(\"Podaw4ć letni lub chłodny.\")` → `false` (cooking instruction after OCR norm)\n\n### Integration tests (eval loop)\n\nRun the full evaluation suite against all 111 test files. Expected outcomes:\n- 0 regressions on currently-passing files\n- 8 newly-passing files (all except Mushroom Risotto)\n- Target: ≥99% combined accuracy (≤2 failures)\n\n---\n\n## Performance Considerations\n\nAll changes are O(1) per candidate (regex replacements, string checks). No additional embedding calls. No new async operations. Total impact on extraction time: negligible (< 1ms).\n\n---\n\n## Implementation Order\n\nChanges are independent and can be implemented in any order. However, the recommended order maximizes incremental testability:\n\n1. **Change B** (garbled multi-word) — simplest, one check addition, fixes Pattern 3\n2. **Change C** (Polish verbs) — small regex expansion, fixes Pattern 2 partially\n3. **Change D** (OCR-normalized instruction check) — completes Pattern 2 fix\n4. **Change A** (mixed-case OCR repair) — addresses Patterns 1, 4, 7\n5. **Change F** (trailing page ref) — minor cleanup\n6. **Change E** (positional bonus) — Pattern 5, needs investigation if still needed after A–D\n\n---\n\n## Open Questions\n\n1. **Pattern 5 root cause:** Is `OGÓRKOWA ZUPA` actually entering the candidate pool? If the raw embedding score for Polish ALL_CAPS is very negative, Change E alone may not suffice. May need to log scoring details for this specific test case during implementation.\n\n2. **Dictionary coverage for `with/the/a`:** The food dictionary includes `\"with\"` (line 135), so `w1th` should be dictionary-repaired to `with`. If the dictionary-guided repair already fixes most artifacts for Patterns 1–2, the blind repair improvement (Change A) may be redundant for those cases. But it's still needed for Pattern 7 and words not in the dictionary.\n\n3. **`4→a` lookaround precision:** The current `0→O` substitution in the ALL_CAPS branch uses `(?<=[A-ZÀ-Ż])0` — requiring adjacent uppercase. For mixed-case, should we require BOTH adjacent characters to be letters, or just one? Single-sided lookaround matches more cases but has a slightly higher false-positive risk (e.g., `m4` in an ingredient line like `300g m4ki pszenne`). However, ingredient lines are already filtered by `looksLikeIngredient`, so the risk is minimal.\n\n---\n\n## Failure → Fix Mapping\n\n| Pattern | Failures | Root cause | Primary fix | Secondary fix |\n|---------|----------|-----------|-------------|---------------|\n| 1: OCR → empty | 2 | Corrupted title rejected, no fallback | A (complete OCR repair) | E (relaxed fallback) |\n| 2: OCR → wrong body | 2 | Body line (`Podaw4ć...`) outscores title | C (Polish verbs) + D (OCR-norm filter) | A (better repair) |\n| 3: Garbage → wrong body | 1 | `XxYyZz` evades garbled check | B (multi-word garbled) | — |\n| 4: Erratic case → wrong body | 1 | `Ugotuj ziemniaky. (38)` wins | C (Polish verbs) + A (OCR repair) | F (page ref strip) |\n| 5: Metadata → empty | 1 | Polish ALL_CAPS weak embedding | E (positional bonus) | A (may help indirectly) |\n| 6: Title absent | 1 | Structural problem | **Not fixable** | — |\n| 7: Partial OCR | 1 | `0→o` missing in mixed-case | A (complete OCR repair) | — |\n","numLines":301,"startLine":1,"totalLines":301}}}
