{"type":"user","message":{"role":"user","content":[{"tool_use_id":"toolu_01PmNeJVKE3gsZGvEHkruEKg","type":"tool_result","content":[{"type":"text","text":"Now I have enough context. Let me compile the analysis.\n\n---\n\n## Cross-Iteration Contradiction Analysis: Iteration 29 Plan\n\nAfter reviewing all 28 prior improvement plans, here are the findings organized by each proposed change in iteration 29.\n\n---\n\n### CONTRADICTION 1 (Medium Severity): Change E -- rawScore threshold relaxation conflicts with iteration 7/8 safety design\n\n**Iteration 29 proposes:** Relax the rawScore threshold from `-0.05` to `-0.10` for candidates with \"structural evidence\" (first-after-preamble or direct-successor).\n\n**History:**\n- **Iteration 7** (`/Users/eryk.napierala/Projects/fasola/tools/title-loop/docs/7-9a83c46/improvement-plan.md`) introduced the empty-pool fallback with an initial threshold of `rawScore > 0.02` for all positions, specifically noting that the `0.02` guard was \"added to prevent ingredient-line leakage.\"\n- **Iteration 8** (`/Users/eryk.napierala/Projects/fasola/tools/title-loop/docs/8-b5177f1/improvement-plan.md`) introduced the position-aware relaxation to `-0.05` for positions 0-2, explicitly calling this out as a deliberate boundary: \"The -0.05 lower bound prevents candidates with actively negative signal (more header-like than title-like) from leaking through.\"\n- **Iteration 26** (`/Users/eryk.napierala/Projects/fasola/tools/title-loop/docs/26-e8ee23c/improvement-plan.md`) kept the `-0.05` threshold and added a combined positional boost cap of `+0.15` to prevent over-boosting.\n\nIteration 29 proposes lowering to `-0.10`, meaning candidates that are **actively anti-title** (embedding similarity closer to headers/noise than to titles) would now be selected. The iteration 8 plan explicitly designed the `-0.05` floor to prevent this exact scenario. Iteration 29 does not acknowledge this prior reasoning or explain why the original concern is no longer valid.\n\n**Recommendation:** Acknowledge the iteration 8 rationale explicitly. If lowering to `-0.10` is necessary, provide evidence that the structural-evidence guard is sufficient to prevent the ingredient/header leakage that iteration 8 was guarding against. Consider keeping `-0.05` but instead increasing the preamble bonus (Part 2 of Change E) to push candidates above the existing threshold rather than lowering the floor.\n\n---\n\n### CONTRADICTION 2 (Medium Severity): Change E -- preamble bonus increase from 0.12 to 0.15 conflicts with iteration 26's cap\n\n**Iteration 29 proposes:** Increase the preamble bonus from `0.12` to `0.15` for pipe-separated metadata + ALL_CAPS patterns, noting \"The cap at +0.15 (line 1182) prevents over-boosting.\"\n\n**History:**\n- **Iteration 24** (`/Users/eryk.napierala/Projects/fasola/tools/title-loop/docs/24-b15aa30/improvement-plan.md`) introduced the first-after-preamble bonus at `+0.08`.\n- **Iteration 26** (`/Users/eryk.napierala/Projects/fasola/tools/title-loop/docs/26-e8ee23c/improvement-plan.md`) raised the first-after-preamble bonus to `+0.12` for section-label preambles, but explicitly introduced a combined cap of `+0.15` when both the preamble bonus and the candidate-relative position bonus fire together. The plan stated: \"To prevent over-boosting non-title candidates: make the first-after-preamble bonus and candidate-relative position bonus partially exclusive -- if both apply, cap their combined contribution at +0.15.\"\n- **Iteration 27** (`/Users/eryk.napierala/Projects/fasola/tools/title-loop/docs/27-51f970e/improvement-plan.md`) introduced the direct-successor bonus (`+0.10`) that also shares the `maxPositionalBoost` cap of `+0.15`.\n\nIf iteration 29 sets the preamble bonus itself to `0.15`, it would hit the cap on its own, leaving zero headroom for the direct-successor bonus or candidate-relative position bonus to contribute. More critically, if the code has the cap at `+0.15` and the preamble bonus is also `+0.15`, the candidate-relative position bonus effectively becomes dead code for these cases. This is not a contradiction per se, but it undermines the layered bonus system that iterations 24, 26, and 27 carefully designed.\n\n**Recommendation:** Keep the preamble bonus at `0.12` and instead either (a) raise the combined cap from `0.15` to `0.18` if more boost is needed, or (b) address the root cause (weak MiniLM embeddings for Polish ALL_CAPS) through OCR repair (Change A) rather than positional override.\n\n---\n\n### CONTRADICTION 3 (Low Severity): Change A -- `4->a` and `5->s` in mixed-case blind repair is consistent with prior design intent but needs caution around iteration 24's dictionary-guided approach\n\n**Iteration 29 proposes:** Add `0->o`, `4->a`, `5->s` substitutions to the mixed-case branch of `applyBlindOcrRepairToken`.\n\n**History:**\n- **Iteration 24** (`/Users/eryk.napierala/Projects/fasola/tools/title-loop/docs/24-b15aa30/improvement-plan.md`) introduced dictionary-guided OCR repair as the primary approach, explicitly noting: \"The fundamental flaw: digit-to-letter mapping is ambiguous without word-level context. `1` can be `I`, `L`, or `l` depending on the word. Post-hoc substitution on the final title string can't resolve this ambiguity.\" The plan's core thesis was that blind substitution is inferior to dictionary-guided repair.\n- **Iteration 27** (`/Users/eryk.napierala/Projects/fasola/tools/title-loop/docs/27-51f970e/improvement-plan.md`) acknowledged this by positioning blind repair as \"complementary, not a replacement\" for dictionary-guided repair, limited to early-position candidates.\n- **Iteration 28** (`/Users/eryk.napierala/Projects/fasola/tools/title-loop/docs/28-1ac016c/improvement-plan.md`) introduced the dual-variant approach (both `i` and `l` variants) specifically because blind `1->l` was producing wrong results.\n\nThis is not a strict contradiction -- iteration 29's Change A is consistent with the incremental expansion of blind repair. However, the `4->a` substitution specifically could create false positives for legitimate digits in text like `m4ki` (where `4` might actually be a digit in some context). Iteration 24 warned about exactly this ambiguity. The lookaround guards in iter 29 mitigate this, but iter 29's own Open Question 3 acknowledges the risk.\n\n**Recommendation:** This is fine as proposed. The lookaround guards and the fact that ingredient lines are already filtered provide sufficient safety. Just note that this further expands the blind repair path that iteration 24 explicitly designed the dictionary approach to avoid.\n\n---\n\n### CONTRADICTION 4 (None -- Clean Extension): Change C -- Polish cooking verb expansion is consistent with iterations 19 and 21\n\n**History:**\n- **Iteration 18** (`/Users/eryk.napierala/Projects/fasola/tools/title-loop/docs/18-1d256ae/improvement-plan.md`) introduced `looksLikeCookingInstruction` with English cooking verbs.\n- **Iteration 19** (`/Users/eryk.napierala/Projects/fasola/tools/title-loop/docs/19-55b161b/improvement-plan.md`) added `POLISH_COOKING_INSTRUCTION_STARTS` with a large set of Polish imperative verbs, explicitly noting the distinction between imperatives (`Smaż`) and past participles/adjectives (`Smażona`) used in titles.\n- **Iteration 21** (`/Users/eryk.napierala/Projects/fasola/tools/title-loop/docs/21-f1e3c51/improvement-plan.md`) noted that `looksLikeCookingInstruction` was already working well for Polish.\n- **Iteration 24** added more missing English verbs (\"scatter\", \"score\", \"pat\", etc.).\n\nIteration 29's proposed additions (`ugotuj`, `upiecz`, `podawać`, `zapiekaj`, `obtocz`, `podgrzej`) are clean extensions of the existing verb list. The `u-` prefix forms (perfective) are a legitimate gap that iteration 19 did not cover. No contradiction.\n\nHowever, one nuance: `podawać` is an **infinitive** form, not an imperative. Iteration 19 specifically designed `POLISH_COOKING_INSTRUCTION_STARTS` around **imperative** verbs. The infinitive `podawać` (\"to serve\") could theoretically start a recipe name like \"Podawać z sosem\" (though this would be unusual). This is a minor stylistic departure from the established pattern, not a functional contradiction.\n\n**Recommendation:** Clean. Just verify that `podawać` never starts a Polish recipe title in the test corpus.\n\n---\n\n### CONTRADICTION 5 (None -- Clean Extension): Change B -- multi-word garbled detection\n\nNo prior iteration restricted the garbled check to single words by design. The single-word limitation appears to be an oversight, not a deliberate decision. Iterations 5, 6, and 14 refined garbled detection but never discussed multi-word behavior. The `Mc`/`Mac` exemption in iteration 29 is a reasonable precaution.\n\n**No contradiction found.**\n\n---\n\n### CONTRADICTION 6 (None -- Clean Extension): Change F -- trailing `(N)` page number stripping\n\n- **Iteration 12** (`/Users/eryk.napierala/Projects/fasola/tools/title-loop/docs/12-0b9bd80/improvement-plan.md`) added `stripParentheticalGloss` for English translation parentheticals.\n- **Iteration 18** added parenthetical handling in case normalization.\n\nNeither iteration addressed numeric parentheticals like `(38)`. Change F is a new rule that does not conflict with existing stripping logic. The `stripParentheticalGloss` function preserves ALL_CAPS parentheticals like `(VARIATION D)`, and Change F's regex specifically targets `\\d{1,4}` -- these are non-overlapping patterns.\n\n**No contradiction found.**\n\n---\n\n### CONTRADICTION 7 (Low Severity): Change D -- Pre-filter OCR normalization (`4->a`) before cooking instruction detection touches the same concern as iteration 24\n\n**Iteration 24** explicitly moved OCR repair to happen **before** embedding scoring (pre-scoring repair on candidates). Iteration 29's Change D applies a lighter version of this idea specifically for the cooking instruction filter in `passesHardFilters`. This is architecturally consistent but introduces a second OCR normalization path (one in `buildCandidates` for embedding, one in `passesHardFilters` for filtering). If these two paths diverge in their substitution rules, a candidate could be filtered with different text than what it was scored with.\n\n**Recommendation:** Ensure both OCR normalization paths use the same substitution rules, or extract the normalization into a shared utility.\n\n---\n\n## Summary\n\n| Change | Contradictions Found | Severity | Action Needed |\n|--------|---------------------|----------|---------------|\n| A: Mixed-case OCR `0->o`, `4->a`, `5->s` | Mild tension with iter 24's dictionary-first philosophy | Low | OK as-is with lookaround guards |\n| B: Multi-word garbled detection | None | -- | Clean |\n| C: Polish cooking verb expansion | None (minor: `podawać` is infinitive, not imperative) | -- | Clean |\n| D: Pre-filter OCR normalization | Architectural consistency concern with iter 24 | Low | Share normalization logic |\n| E: Strengthen preamble bonus + relax threshold | **Conflicts with iter 8 (`-0.05` floor) and iter 26 (cap design)** | Medium | Acknowledge iter 8 rationale; reconsider approach |\n| F: Trailing `(N)` stripping | None | -- | Clean |\n\nThe most significant finding is **Change E**, which proposes relaxing the rawScore threshold to `-0.10` without acknowledging that iteration 8 specifically set the `-0.05` floor to prevent header/ingredient leakage, and which sets the preamble bonus to the same value as the combined cap, effectively neutralizing the layered bonus system from iterations 24/26/27. The other changes are clean extensions of existing patterns with no meaningful contradictions."},{"type":"text","text":"agentId: a765e7ba605174d02 (for resuming to continue this agent's work if needed)\n<usage>total_tokens: 58321\ntool_uses: 31\nduration_ms: 161158</usage>"}]}]},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"a92866c1-134f-4711-bade-a1c8bcc36679","uuid":"9d820de4-f2dd-4e1f-8c99-53e94793891e","tool_use_result":{"status":"completed","prompt":"I need you to check for cross-iteration contradictions in an improvement plan for a title extraction system. \n\nThe current plan is iteration 29 (at tools/title-loop/docs/29-e7e3098/improvement-plan.md). I need you to read previous iteration improvement plans and check if the current plan proposes changes that CONTRADICT or REVERSE changes made in earlier iterations.\n\nKey changes in the current plan (iteration 29):\n- Change A: Add `0→o`, `4→a`, `5→s` substitutions to mixed-case blind OCR repair\n- Change B: Expand garbled token detection to multi-word candidates (check individual words for [a-z][A-Z] transitions)\n- Change C: Expand Polish cooking verb filter with ugotuj, upiecz, podawać, zapiekaj, obtocz, podgrzej\n- Change D: Pre-filter OCR normalization (4→a) before cooking instruction detection\n- Change E: Strengthen first-after-metadata positional bonus, relax rawScore threshold\n- Change F: Add trailing `(N)` page/step number stripping\n\nPlease read ALL previous improvement plans (iterations 1 through 28) and look for:\n1. Any previous iteration that changed heuristics in the OPPOSITE direction of what iter 29 proposes\n2. Any rule that was added in a previous iteration to fix a specific failure that iter 29 would weaken/remove\n3. Any threshold/weight tuning from previous iterations that iter 29 changes without acknowledging\n4. Any previous iteration that tried something similar to what iter 29 proposes and found it problematic\n\nThe plans are at: tools/title-loop/docs/*/improvement-plan.md (where * is like \"1-404c596\", \"2-072e8fb\", etc.)\n\nRead at least the recent iterations (20+) carefully, and spot-check earlier ones. Report any contradictions found with specific iteration numbers and details.","agentId":"a765e7ba605174d02","content":[{"type":"text","text":"Now I have enough context. Let me compile the analysis.\n\n---\n\n## Cross-Iteration Contradiction Analysis: Iteration 29 Plan\n\nAfter reviewing all 28 prior improvement plans, here are the findings organized by each proposed change in iteration 29.\n\n---\n\n### CONTRADICTION 1 (Medium Severity): Change E -- rawScore threshold relaxation conflicts with iteration 7/8 safety design\n\n**Iteration 29 proposes:** Relax the rawScore threshold from `-0.05` to `-0.10` for candidates with \"structural evidence\" (first-after-preamble or direct-successor).\n\n**History:**\n- **Iteration 7** (`/Users/eryk.napierala/Projects/fasola/tools/title-loop/docs/7-9a83c46/improvement-plan.md`) introduced the empty-pool fallback with an initial threshold of `rawScore > 0.02` for all positions, specifically noting that the `0.02` guard was \"added to prevent ingredient-line leakage.\"\n- **Iteration 8** (`/Users/eryk.napierala/Projects/fasola/tools/title-loop/docs/8-b5177f1/improvement-plan.md`) introduced the position-aware relaxation to `-0.05` for positions 0-2, explicitly calling this out as a deliberate boundary: \"The -0.05 lower bound prevents candidates with actively negative signal (more header-like than title-like) from leaking through.\"\n- **Iteration 26** (`/Users/eryk.napierala/Projects/fasola/tools/title-loop/docs/26-e8ee23c/improvement-plan.md`) kept the `-0.05` threshold and added a combined positional boost cap of `+0.15` to prevent over-boosting.\n\nIteration 29 proposes lowering to `-0.10`, meaning candidates that are **actively anti-title** (embedding similarity closer to headers/noise than to titles) would now be selected. The iteration 8 plan explicitly designed the `-0.05` floor to prevent this exact scenario. Iteration 29 does not acknowledge this prior reasoning or explain why the original concern is no longer valid.\n\n**Recommendation:** Acknowledge the iteration 8 rationale explicitly. If lowering to `-0.10` is necessary, provide evidence that the structural-evidence guard is sufficient to prevent the ingredient/header leakage that iteration 8 was guarding against. Consider keeping `-0.05` but instead increasing the preamble bonus (Part 2 of Change E) to push candidates above the existing threshold rather than lowering the floor.\n\n---\n\n### CONTRADICTION 2 (Medium Severity): Change E -- preamble bonus increase from 0.12 to 0.15 conflicts with iteration 26's cap\n\n**Iteration 29 proposes:** Increase the preamble bonus from `0.12` to `0.15` for pipe-separated metadata + ALL_CAPS patterns, noting \"The cap at +0.15 (line 1182) prevents over-boosting.\"\n\n**History:**\n- **Iteration 24** (`/Users/eryk.napierala/Projects/fasola/tools/title-loop/docs/24-b15aa30/improvement-plan.md`) introduced the first-after-preamble bonus at `+0.08`.\n- **Iteration 26** (`/Users/eryk.napierala/Projects/fasola/tools/title-loop/docs/26-e8ee23c/improvement-plan.md`) raised the first-after-preamble bonus to `+0.12` for section-label preambles, but explicitly introduced a combined cap of `+0.15` when both the preamble bonus and the candidate-relative position bonus fire together. The plan stated: \"To prevent over-boosting non-title candidates: make the first-after-preamble bonus and candidate-relative position bonus partially exclusive -- if both apply, cap their combined contribution at +0.15.\"\n- **Iteration 27** (`/Users/eryk.napierala/Projects/fasola/tools/title-loop/docs/27-51f970e/improvement-plan.md`) introduced the direct-successor bonus (`+0.10`) that also shares the `maxPositionalBoost` cap of `+0.15`.\n\nIf iteration 29 sets the preamble bonus itself to `0.15`, it would hit the cap on its own, leaving zero headroom for the direct-successor bonus or candidate-relative position bonus to contribute. More critically, if the code has the cap at `+0.15` and the preamble bonus is also `+0.15`, the candidate-relative position bonus effectively becomes dead code for these cases. This is not a contradiction per se, but it undermines the layered bonus system that iterations 24, 26, and 27 carefully designed.\n\n**Recommendation:** Keep the preamble bonus at `0.12` and instead either (a) raise the combined cap from `0.15` to `0.18` if more boost is needed, or (b) address the root cause (weak MiniLM embeddings for Polish ALL_CAPS) through OCR repair (Change A) rather than positional override.\n\n---\n\n### CONTRADICTION 3 (Low Severity): Change A -- `4->a` and `5->s` in mixed-case blind repair is consistent with prior design intent but needs caution around iteration 24's dictionary-guided approach\n\n**Iteration 29 proposes:** Add `0->o`, `4->a`, `5->s` substitutions to the mixed-case branch of `applyBlindOcrRepairToken`.\n\n**History:**\n- **Iteration 24** (`/Users/eryk.napierala/Projects/fasola/tools/title-loop/docs/24-b15aa30/improvement-plan.md`) introduced dictionary-guided OCR repair as the primary approach, explicitly noting: \"The fundamental flaw: digit-to-letter mapping is ambiguous without word-level context. `1` can be `I`, `L`, or `l` depending on the word. Post-hoc substitution on the final title string can't resolve this ambiguity.\" The plan's core thesis was that blind substitution is inferior to dictionary-guided repair.\n- **Iteration 27** (`/Users/eryk.napierala/Projects/fasola/tools/title-loop/docs/27-51f970e/improvement-plan.md`) acknowledged this by positioning blind repair as \"complementary, not a replacement\" for dictionary-guided repair, limited to early-position candidates.\n- **Iteration 28** (`/Users/eryk.napierala/Projects/fasola/tools/title-loop/docs/28-1ac016c/improvement-plan.md`) introduced the dual-variant approach (both `i` and `l` variants) specifically because blind `1->l` was producing wrong results.\n\nThis is not a strict contradiction -- iteration 29's Change A is consistent with the incremental expansion of blind repair. However, the `4->a` substitution specifically could create false positives for legitimate digits in text like `m4ki` (where `4` might actually be a digit in some context). Iteration 24 warned about exactly this ambiguity. The lookaround guards in iter 29 mitigate this, but iter 29's own Open Question 3 acknowledges the risk.\n\n**Recommendation:** This is fine as proposed. The lookaround guards and the fact that ingredient lines are already filtered provide sufficient safety. Just note that this further expands the blind repair path that iteration 24 explicitly designed the dictionary approach to avoid.\n\n---\n\n### CONTRADICTION 4 (None -- Clean Extension): Change C -- Polish cooking verb expansion is consistent with iterations 19 and 21\n\n**History:**\n- **Iteration 18** (`/Users/eryk.napierala/Projects/fasola/tools/title-loop/docs/18-1d256ae/improvement-plan.md`) introduced `looksLikeCookingInstruction` with English cooking verbs.\n- **Iteration 19** (`/Users/eryk.napierala/Projects/fasola/tools/title-loop/docs/19-55b161b/improvement-plan.md`) added `POLISH_COOKING_INSTRUCTION_STARTS` with a large set of Polish imperative verbs, explicitly noting the distinction between imperatives (`Smaż`) and past participles/adjectives (`Smażona`) used in titles.\n- **Iteration 21** (`/Users/eryk.napierala/Projects/fasola/tools/title-loop/docs/21-f1e3c51/improvement-plan.md`) noted that `looksLikeCookingInstruction` was already working well for Polish.\n- **Iteration 24** added more missing English verbs (\"scatter\", \"score\", \"pat\", etc.).\n\nIteration 29's proposed additions (`ugotuj`, `upiecz`, `podawać`, `zapiekaj`, `obtocz`, `podgrzej`) are clean extensions of the existing verb list. The `u-` prefix forms (perfective) are a legitimate gap that iteration 19 did not cover. No contradiction.\n\nHowever, one nuance: `podawać` is an **infinitive** form, not an imperative. Iteration 19 specifically designed `POLISH_COOKING_INSTRUCTION_STARTS` around **imperative** verbs. The infinitive `podawać` (\"to serve\") could theoretically start a recipe name like \"Podawać z sosem\" (though this would be unusual). This is a minor stylistic departure from the established pattern, not a functional contradiction.\n\n**Recommendation:** Clean. Just verify that `podawać` never starts a Polish recipe title in the test corpus.\n\n---\n\n### CONTRADICTION 5 (None -- Clean Extension): Change B -- multi-word garbled detection\n\nNo prior iteration restricted the garbled check to single words by design. The single-word limitation appears to be an oversight, not a deliberate decision. Iterations 5, 6, and 14 refined garbled detection but never discussed multi-word behavior. The `Mc`/`Mac` exemption in iteration 29 is a reasonable precaution.\n\n**No contradiction found.**\n\n---\n\n### CONTRADICTION 6 (None -- Clean Extension): Change F -- trailing `(N)` page number stripping\n\n- **Iteration 12** (`/Users/eryk.napierala/Projects/fasola/tools/title-loop/docs/12-0b9bd80/improvement-plan.md`) added `stripParentheticalGloss` for English translation parentheticals.\n- **Iteration 18** added parenthetical handling in case normalization.\n\nNeither iteration addressed numeric parentheticals like `(38)`. Change F is a new rule that does not conflict with existing stripping logic. The `stripParentheticalGloss` function preserves ALL_CAPS parentheticals like `(VARIATION D)`, and Change F's regex specifically targets `\\d{1,4}` -- these are non-overlapping patterns.\n\n**No contradiction found.**\n\n---\n\n### CONTRADICTION 7 (Low Severity): Change D -- Pre-filter OCR normalization (`4->a`) before cooking instruction detection touches the same concern as iteration 24\n\n**Iteration 24** explicitly moved OCR repair to happen **before** embedding scoring (pre-scoring repair on candidates). Iteration 29's Change D applies a lighter version of this idea specifically for the cooking instruction filter in `passesHardFilters`. This is architecturally consistent but introduces a second OCR normalization path (one in `buildCandidates` for embedding, one in `passesHardFilters` for filtering). If these two paths diverge in their substitution rules, a candidate could be filtered with different text than what it was scored with.\n\n**Recommendation:** Ensure both OCR normalization paths use the same substitution rules, or extract the normalization into a shared utility.\n\n---\n\n## Summary\n\n| Change | Contradictions Found | Severity | Action Needed |\n|--------|---------------------|----------|---------------|\n| A: Mixed-case OCR `0->o`, `4->a`, `5->s` | Mild tension with iter 24's dictionary-first philosophy | Low | OK as-is with lookaround guards |\n| B: Multi-word garbled detection | None | -- | Clean |\n| C: Polish cooking verb expansion | None (minor: `podawać` is infinitive, not imperative) | -- | Clean |\n| D: Pre-filter OCR normalization | Architectural consistency concern with iter 24 | Low | Share normalization logic |\n| E: Strengthen preamble bonus + relax threshold | **Conflicts with iter 8 (`-0.05` floor) and iter 26 (cap design)** | Medium | Acknowledge iter 8 rationale; reconsider approach |\n| F: Trailing `(N)` stripping | None | -- | Clean |\n\nThe most significant finding is **Change E**, which proposes relaxing the rawScore threshold to `-0.10` without acknowledging that iteration 8 specifically set the `-0.05` floor to prevent header/ingredient leakage, and which sets the preamble bonus to the same value as the combined cap, effectively neutralizing the layered bonus system from iterations 24/26/27. The other changes are clean extensions of existing patterns with no meaningful contradictions."}],"totalDurationMs":161158,"totalTokens":58321,"totalToolUseCount":31,"usage":{"input_tokens":1,"cache_creation_input_tokens":1669,"cache_read_input_tokens":53560,"output_tokens":3091,"server_tool_use":{"web_search_requests":0,"web_fetch_requests":0},"service_tier":"standard","cache_creation":{"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":0,"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":1669},"inference_geo":"","iterations":[],"speed":"standard"}}}
